00:42:02.000 --> 00:42:07.066
And so there is no way in the
macroscopic world that we're

00:42:07.066 --> 00:42:11.688
going to see any effects,
any wave-like behavior from

00:42:11.688 --> 00:42:16.133
macroscopic objects.
Our wavelengths are too small.

00:42:16.133 --> 00:42:20.222
There is no way to see that
wave-like behavior.

00:42:20.222 --> 00:42:25.555
You're going to need slits or
you're going to need atoms that

00:42:25.555 --> 00:42:30.000
are about 10^-33 meters from
each other.

00:42:30.000 --> 00:42:36.116
And that's just not practical.
For macroscopic objects,

00:42:36.116 --> 00:42:40.760
for you and me,
our wavelengths don't mean

00:42:40.760 --> 00:42:45.064
anything.
They are of no consequence in

00:42:45.064 --> 00:42:49.595
the observation of what we see
around us.

00:42:49.595 --> 00:42:56.051
However, they have lots of
consequences for particles such

00:42:56.051 --> 00:43:02.394
as an electron whose environment
is on the scale of their

00:43:02.394 --> 00:43:06.434
wavelength.
I am saying here,

00:43:06.434 --> 00:43:11.412
in this case for the electron
where the wavelength is 10^-10

00:43:11.412 --> 00:43:16.728
meters, is that is a wavelength
that is on the order of the size

00:43:16.728 --> 00:43:20.103
of the electron's environment in
an atom.

00:43:20.103 --> 00:43:23.140
That's 10^-10 meters.
In those cases,

00:43:23.140 --> 00:43:27.949
when that wavelength is about
the size of the environment,

00:43:27.949 --> 00:43:32.000
then the wave-like properties
matter.

00:43:32.000 --> 00:43:35.282
They matter.
